  <section id="problem" class="cs-section container">
    <div class="cs-kicker">01 &mdash; PROBLEM</div>
    <h2 class="cs-h2 cs-h2--narrow">Providers work in the field &mdash; the platform lived on a desktop</h2>
    <p class="cs-lead">As of July 2026, BabyQuip supported roughly <strong class="cs-text-emphasis">3,285 Quality Providers (QPs)</strong> across US and international markets. QPs run independent rental businesses: inventory, customer coordination, gear preparation, delivery, pickup, and recovery across their own service areas.</p>
    <p class="cs-lead">Much of that work happens away from a computer, yet the reservation, messaging, transfer, and modification workflows BabyQuip controls were accessed through a desktop-oriented Partner Portal. The challenge was not to shrink that portal onto a phone. It was to answer a harder question: <strong class="cs-text-emphasis">what should BabyQuip&rsquo;s first provider app be responsible for?</strong></p>

    <div class="cs-pullquote">
      <p>How might we help providers understand and act on active BabyQuip reservations on the go <span class="accent">without recreating the entire Partner Portal?</span></p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="cs-h3 u-mt-lg">A reservation is only the beginning of the provider&rsquo;s work</h3>
    <p class="cs-lead">Once a reservation lands, the provider interprets it, prepares gear, coordinates with the customer, organizes the day, completes delivery and pickup, and returns inventory to a rentable state &mdash; often stitched together with spreadsheets, handwritten sheets, personal calendars, routing tools, SMS, and message templates.</p>
    <div class="cs-callout-box background-white">
      <div class="cs-flow-line">Weekly planning <span class="accent">&rarr;</span> customer coordination <span class="accent">&rarr;</span> gear preparation <span class="accent">&rarr;</span> routing &amp; delivery <span class="accent">&rarr;</span> pickup <span class="accent">&rarr;</span> cleaning &amp; inventory recovery</div>
    </div>
    <p class="cs-lead">Routing surfaced repeatedly as a major unmet need &mdash; but it is a separate product problem involving sequencing, travel time, delivery windows, vehicle capacity, and different operating models. Ignoring it would misunderstand the provider&rsquo;s business; solving it in Phase 1 would turn the first app into a much larger operational platform.</p>

    <h3 class="cs-h3 u-mt-lg">Defining the app&rsquo;s role</h3>
    <div class="cs-compare">
      <div class="cs-compare-cell background-white">
        <div class="cs-callout-label">PARTNER PORTAL</div>
        <div class="cs-flow-line cs-flow-line--muted">Helps QPs administer their BabyQuip business</div>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-compare-cell cs-compare-cell--after">
        <div class="cs-callout-label cs-callout-label--accent">MOBILE APP</div>
        <div class="cs-flow-line">Helps QPs access and act on BabyQuip information while operating that business in the real world</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="cs-lead">The app would focus on the workflows BabyQuip directly owns &mdash; reservations, customer and order details, platform communication, modifications, transfers, and approval-required changes &mdash; rather than replacing the external tools QPs use to run their whole business.</p>

    <div class="cs-callout-box">
      <div class="cs-callout-label">CORE CONSTRAINT &mdash; REUSE, DON&rsquo;T REBUILD</div>
      <p>Phase 1 could not depend on a new routing system, CRM, or operations backend. The question changed from &ldquo;what could a provider operations app eventually become?&rdquo; to <strong class="cs-text-emphasis">&ldquo;what is the smallest set of current BabyQuip capabilities that becomes substantially more useful when reorganized around mobile work?&rdquo;</strong></p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="research" class="cs-section container">
    <div class="cs-kicker">02 &mdash; RESEARCH</div>
    <h2 class="cs-h2 cs-h2--narrow">Combining directional feedback with operational evidence</h2>
    <p class="cs-lead">I triangulated an exploratory five-QP survey with deeper conversations with internal QPs and a Service Desk domain expert, reviews of real workflow artifacts &mdash; handwritten plans, printed lists, message templates, customer text threads &mdash; an audit of the existing Partner Portal, and calendar reviews of provider accounts sampled across the lower, middle, and upper ranges of the Supply Index ranking. I treated the survey as directional and grounded the product decisions in recurring patterns across workflow artifacts, provider conversations, portal audits, and account reviews.</p>

    <h3 class="cs-h3 u-mt-lg">The strongest artifact was a handwritten daily/weekly plan</h3>
    <p class="cs-lead">One provider printed outbound inventory lists, then rewrote each day into a notebook &mdash; route order, delivery windows, customer names, addresses, gear counts, hotel and flight details, confirmation checks, completion marks. It exposed a critical distinction: <strong class="cs-text-emphasis">the reservation was the system record; the operational day was the provider&rsquo;s working object</strong>. Providers were extracting information from BabyQuip and rebuilding it into a more usable operating plan.</p>
    <div class="cs-diagram-grid">
      <div>
        <div class="cs-label">Outbound Inventory</div>
        <img src="img_nootebook1.png" alt="Outbound Inventory">
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="cs-label">Daily plan</div>
        <img src="img_nootebook2.png" alt="Outbound Inventory">

      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="cs-label">Weekly plan</div>
        <img src="img_nootebook3.png" alt="Outbound Inventory">

      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="u-mt-md">
      <div class="cs-media cs-ar-16-10" style="display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;padding:24px;text-align:center">
        <span class="cs-label u-m-0">Handwritten daily plan beside the Partner Portal calendar &mdash; route order &middot; customer/location &middot; gear count &middot; completion state</span>


      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="cs-h3 u-mt-lg">Five findings shaped the architecture</h3>
    <div class="cs-breakdown-grid">
      <div class="cs-breakdown-card">
        <div class="cs-breakdown-tag">1 &middot; Three time horizons</div>
        <p class="cs-text u-mt-xs">Weekly planning (workload, locations, gear), day-before coordination (confirmations, missing details, loading), and day-of execution (next stop, navigation, contact, delays). A generic reservation directory could not serve all three equally.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-breakdown-card">
        <div class="cs-breakdown-tag">2 &middot; Uneven workload density</div>
        <p class="cs-text u-mt-xs">Sampled calendars ranged from nearly empty to densely booked, but workload was unevenly distributed across individual days at every tier. A Today-only home would often look empty or hide upcoming work; a full month view would bury immediate tasks.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-breakdown-card">
        <div class="cs-breakdown-tag">3 &middot; Communication was fulfillment</div>
        <p class="cs-text u-mt-xs">Messages existed to complete operational work &mdash; timing, access codes, gear placement, last-minute changes. Conversations needed reservation context, not a generic standalone messaging feature.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-breakdown-card">
        <div class="cs-breakdown-tag">4 &middot; Context reconstructed across tools</div>
        <p class="cs-text u-mt-xs">A modification email, an inbox search, the reopened order, the customer&rsquo;s notes, then a text. Providers rebuilt active reservation context across multiple BabyQuip surfaces and external tools before they could act.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-breakdown-card">
        <div class="cs-breakdown-tag">5 &middot; Unread &ne; responsibility</div>
        <p class="cs-text u-mt-xs">The portal mixed conversations, confirmations, and modifications into one feed with badges that were hard to interpret or clear. Unread state did not reliably communicate what the provider was responsible for doing.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-breakdown-card">
        <div class="cs-breakdown-tag">&rarr; The reframe</div>
        <p class="cs-text u-mt-xs">These findings shifted the design from organizing information <em>by source</em> to organizing it <em>by required response</em> &mdash; and from a Today or Month view to a week-first default with day-level drill-down.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cs-diagram-grid">
      <div>
        <div class="cs-label">LOWER SUPPLY INDEX TIER</div>
        <div class="cs-media cs-ar-4-3" style="display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;padding:16px;text-align:center">
